<subSubSection id="C30F0386B13AFF9FFF20FF05FC9BFF41" box="[174,797,223,250]" pageId="15" pageNumber="126" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph id="8BAA500DB13AFF9FFF20FF05FC9BFF41" blockId="15.[174,797,223,250]" box="[174,797,223,250]" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">
T y p e s p e c i e s: 
<taxonomicName id="4C152B8EB13AFF9FFE0EFF3AFC9CFF41" authority="Aldrich, 1928: 2" authorityName="Aldrich" authorityPageNumber="2" authorityYear="1928" box="[384,794,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Adapsilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flaviseta">
<emphasis id="B9618C1FB13AFF9FFE0EFF3AFDD3FF41" box="[384,597,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">Adapsilia flaviseta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF842DFCB13AFF9FFDD2FF3AFC9CFF41" author="Aldrich, J. M." box="[604,794,223,249]" pageId="15" pageNumber="126" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref10277" refString="Aldrich, J. M. Five new parasitic flies reared from beetles in China and India // Proceedings of the U. S. National Museum. - 1928. - 74, N 8. - P. 1 - 7." type="journal article" year="1928">Aldrich, 1928: 2</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30F0386B13AFF9FFF6DFEC5FBC2FE21" pageId="15" pageNumber="126" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAA500DB13AFF9FFF6DFEC5FBC2FE21" blockId="15.[174,1233,287,570]" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">
D i a g n o s i s. The 
<typeStatus id="54AEEEAFB13AFF9FFE31FEC5FE77FE82" box="[447,497,288,314]" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">type</typeStatus>
species in its robust body and widely brown wing and legs, as well as female aculeus and male genitalia structure agrees with 
<taxonomicName id="4C152B8EB13AFF9FFC06FEA5FC79FEE1" authorityName="Coquillett" authorityYear="1898" box="[904,1023,320,345]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Eupyrgota" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis id="B9618C1FB13AFF9FFC06FEA5FC79FEE1" box="[904,1023,320,345]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">Eupyrgota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2523164B13AFF9FFB88FEA5FBC5FEE2" box="[1030,1091,320,346]" pageId="15" pageNumber="126" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differing by the structure of the apico-ventral portion of the oviscape (a “sucker” instead of hooks); the only species can be recognized also from. See also remarks for 
<taxonomicName id="4C152B8EB13AFF9FFC04FE65FBC7FE21" authorityName="Aldrich" authorityYear="1928" box="[906,1089,383,410]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Adapsilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flaviseta" subGenus="Asipyrgota">
<emphasis id="B9618C1FB13AFF9FFC04FE65FC27FE21" box="[906,929,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">E.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B9618C1FB13AFF9FFC3CFE65FC4AFE22" box="[946,972,384,410]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">A.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B9618C1FB13AFF9FFC53FE9AFBC7FE21" box="[989,1089,383,409]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">flaviseta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9618C1FB13AFF9FFBCEFE9AFBC2FE21" box="[1088,1092,383,409]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30F0386B13AFF9FFF6DFE45FCD0FD82" pageId="15" pageNumber="126" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BAA500DB13AFF9FFF6DFE45FCD0FD82" blockId="15.[174,1233,287,570]" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Moderately large, robust species; widely and uniformly darkened; scutellum with 3 pairs of setae; fore and mid trochanters of female without spiny or hooklike setulae; oviscape without ventral hooks, but with desclerotized U-shaped area and narrower oval sucker-like area inside, rimmed with narrow bare area (
<figureCitation id="132E4C88B13AFF9FFC62FE1AFBAFFDA1" box="[1004,1065,511,537]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[166,199,1588,1610]" captionTargetBox="[241,1189,195,1506]" captionTargetId="figure-8@16.[240,1189,195,1510]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 8. Eupyrgota flaviseta, holotype ♀ (1–6), paratypes ♀ (7–9) and} (10–14) (USNM): 1 — habitus, left; 2 — labels; 3–4 — head (3 — left; 4 — dorsal); 5 — fore femur and tibia, posterior view; 6 — mid femur, anterior view; 7 — epandrium, right; 8–9 — phallus glans, right and ventral; 10 — abdomen, dorsal; 11 — same, ventral, macerated in KOH; 12 — oviscape apex, ventrally; 13 — aculeus, ventral; 14 — spermathecae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6403949" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6403949/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">fig. 8</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B9618C1FB13AFF9FFBB8FE1AFBFBFDA1" box="[1078,1149,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">11, 12</emphasis>
). Male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="132E4C88B13AFF9FFEAFFDFAFEDBFD81" box="[289,349,543,569]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[166,199,1588,1610]" captionTargetBox="[241,1189,195,1506]" captionTargetId="figure-8@16.[240,1189,195,1510]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 8. Eupyrgota flaviseta, holotype ♀ (1–6), paratypes ♀ (7–9) and} (10–14) (USNM): 1 — habitus, left; 2 — labels; 3–4 — head (3 — left; 4 — dorsal); 5 — fore femur and tibia, posterior view; 6 — mid femur, anterior view; 7 — epandrium, right; 8–9 — phallus glans, right and ventral; 10 — abdomen, dorsal; 11 — same, ventral, macerated in KOH; 12 — oviscape apex, ventrally; 13 — aculeus, ventral; 14 — spermathecae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6403949" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6403949/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">fig. 8</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="B9618C1FB13AFF9FFEE7FDFAFE12FD81" box="[361,404,543,569]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">
<figureCitation id="132E4C88B13AFF9FFEE7FDFAFEF1FD81" box="[361,375,543,569]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[166,199,1721,1743]" captionTargetBox="[190,1222,602,1675]" captionTargetId="figure-128@14.[166,1231,602,1679]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 7. Eupyrgota vespiformis, ♀ (NMKE): 1 — habitus, left; 2–4 — head (2 — anterior left; 3 — left anterior; 4 — dorsal); 5 — wing; 6–7 — abdomen (6 — left; 7— dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6403947" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6403947/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">7</figureCitation>
–9
</emphasis>
) similar to those in 
<taxonomicName id="4C152B8EB13AFF9FFDF1FDC5FD70FD81" authorityName="Coquillett" authorityYear="1898" box="[639,758,544,569]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Eupyrgota" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9618C1FB13AFF9FFDF1FDC5FD70FD81" box="[639,758,544,569]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="126">Eupyrgota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(s. str.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
